efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(1)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The key observation is that any bit set in k must also be set in n; otherwise we cannot create that 1 by only flipping 1→0. The bitwise AND check (n & k) == k enforces this. The actual number of flips is simply the count of differing bits between n and k where n has a 1 and k has a 0, which is exactly the population count of n XOR k.

